. In the study area, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tomes" authorityYear="1858" box="[816,961,425,451]" class="Mammalia" family="Miniopteridae" genus="Miniopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="438" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[816,961,425,451]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="438">M. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished from other known 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1837" box="[909,1052,459,485]" class="Mammalia" family="Miniopteridae" genus="Miniopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="438" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[909,1052,459,485]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="438">Miniopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the skin color and the smaller size (
<tableCitation box="[1030,1127,493,519]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="10.[99,112,501,522]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="TABLE 2. Measurements of nine external traits of 52 bat species. FA â€” forearm length, BM â€” body mass, HB â€” head and body length, TL â€” tail length, TB â€” tibia length, HF â€” hind foot length, TU â€” thumb length: EL â€” ear length, TR â€” tragus length. Numbers denote minimum and maximum, and sample size; values in parentheses indicate measurements of specimens of this study; â€˜ â€“ â€™: data not available. BMs for specimens were taken in the field. All measurements in mm, except for BM (in g)" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/1DCD6623FFA8BF319968FE17FA147437" pageId="26" pageNumber="438" tableUuid="1DCD6623FFA8BF319968FE17FA147437">Table 2</tableCitation>
